"It is very delicate — ^what I want to say," 
Felix began. "But I have been thinking 
of it for some time." 

"Please to say it as quickly as possible," 
said Mr. Brand. 

" It's because you are a clergyman, you 
know," Felix went on. "I don't think I 
should venture to say it to a common 



man." 



Mr. Brand was silent a moment. "If 
it is a question of yielding to a weakness, of 
resenting an injury, I am afraid I am a very 



common man." 



" My dearest friend," cried Felix, " this is 
not an injury; it's a benefit — a great ser- 
