his identity. It was that of a person who 
had lately been much in her thoughts ; but 
her first impulse, nevertheless, was to turn 
away; the last thing she desired was to have 
the air of coming in quest of Robert Acton. 
The gentleman on the grass, however, gave 
her no time to decide; he could not long 
remain imconscious of so agreeable a pre- 
sence. He rolled back his eyes, stared, 
gave an exclamation, and then jumped up. 
He stood an instant, looking at her. 

" Excuse my ridiculous position," he said. 

" I have just now no sense of the ridicul- 
ous. But, in case you have, don't imagine 
I came to see you." 

"Take care," rejoined Acton, "how you 
put it into my head! I was thinking of 
you. 

" The occupation of extreme leisure ! " 
said the Baroness. " To think of a woman 



