come to be a formidable figure to his uncle, 
who had not yet arrived at definite views as 
to a proper tone. For the first time in his 
life, as I have said, Mr. Wentworth shirked 
a responsibility ; he earnestly desired that it 
might not be laid upon him to determine 
how his nephew's lighter propositions should 
be treated. He lived under an apprehension 
that Felix might yet beguile him into assent 
to doubtful inductions, and his conscience 
instructed him that the best form of vigil- 
ance was the avoidance of discussion. He 
hoped that the pleasant episode of his 
nephew's visit would pass away without 
a further lapse of consistency. 

